2–1186":"1152–1186","1155–1222":"1155–1222","–1228":"–1228","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1130–1175":"1130–1175","1134–Female":"1134–Deceased","1165":"1165","1154":"1154","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1151":"1151","1182":"1182","1228":"1228","1134":"1134","1222":"1222","1155":"1155","before 1175":"before 1175","about 1155":"about 1155","Rylstone, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rylstone, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Rylstone, Yorkshire, England":"Rylstone, Yorkshire, England","Rillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Rillington, Yorkshire, England":"Rillington, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rilston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","habitational name either from Rolleston (Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Staffordshire) and perhaps Rowston (Lincolnshire), Rolston (or Rowlston) in Mappleton (East Yorkshire), or from Rollestone in Upton Pyne, or Rolstone Barton in Morchard Bishop (both in Devon), or Rollestone (Wiltshire), and perhaps Rowlestone (Herefordshire) or Rolstone in Banwell (Somerset). The placenames have various etymological origins, though most are named with the Middle English personal name <i>Rolf</i> or the Old Norse personal name <i>Hrólfr</i> + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘town, settlement’, Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. See   Rolfe  .","variant of   Rollison  , shortened to <i>Rolleson</i> and altered by the addition of an intrusive <i>-t-</i>, as though it were a habitational name in <i>-ston</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Roulston","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire): variant of   Rolston  ."]},{"name":"Rolfe","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Rolf</i>, <i>Roulf</i>, <i>Rou</i>, <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rouf</i>, <i>Rof</i>. Its usual derivation is from Old Norse <i>Hrólfr</i>, <i>Rolf</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’, and occasionally from ancient Germanic <i>Rodulf</i>, of the same origin as <i>Hrólfr</i> (earlier <i>Hróthúlfr</i>) but in a West Frankish form, which the Scandinavian Normans occasionally used. The name was also common in Normandy where it became Old French <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rou</i>, often Latinized as <i>Rollo</i>. See   Ralph   and compare   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and   Rowson  ."]}]},{"name":"Elias","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Greek form (used in the New Testament) of the name of the prophet   Elijah .  It is one of a number of Old Testament names which have come back into favour since the latter part of the 20th century.  See also  Ellis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elias de Rilston I was born in 1152, in Rillington, Yorkshire, England, his father, William de Rilston, was 22 and his mother, F Rilston, was 18. He married Alice de Hebden in 1165, in Rylstone, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1182, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1152–1182":"1152–1182","1154